            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>—“Yes please.”&nbsp;</p>
<p>For almost three months I was greeted with warmth and they knew my order by heart; I was a regular. The day I placed my last order, I never said goodbye — it never felt appropriate. What could I have said? I didn’t actually <em>know </em>these people. I often wonder whether they noticed that I had never returned, if they thought anything of it.&nbsp;</p>
<p>I have scoffed at the notion of going to New York to “find yourself,” but I think, after all, I made a decision to go to find some sort of truth — truth about myself, the world, love, solitude and reality. In some ways, I did find those things: self-reliance, maturity, independence and patience. I know myself better now — my physical strengths and weaknesses, my values, what I want, what I need and even the very worst parts of myself.&nbsp;</p>
<p>For a long time, I've wandered through life without any clear sense of self, but I left with at least some knowledge of who I am. If I had been there for longer and expanded my rituals, who knows what revelations I may have had, but I know that my own development will continue outside the confines — and possibilities — of the city. My rituals here, although perhaps less sacred, allow me to persist and to survive, just as they did in New York.&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>Sarah Derris is a Trinity junior and Recess local arts editor.</em></p>

